  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">BOTHAR Small-Scale Snail Production to Improve Household Nutrition and Incomes</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Farmers, Youth</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Hands-on training of farmers on improved snail production techniques, agroforestry and horticulture; Train farmers on snail marketing/promotion strategies, leadership  and management; Sensitize farmers on human nutrition and basic health tips; Sensitize farmers on gender issues; Sensitize farmers on HIV/AIDS issues</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Poverty and hunger are rife in rural communities where the majority of Cameroon&#x2019;s population lives. Unemployment is high, with more than 80 percent of the population depending on subsistence agriculture. The natural resource exploitation and the indiscriminate spraying by the larger commercial plantations is polluting the environment and exterminating snails and other wildlife. Snail-hunting is traditional among rural households in southern Cameroon. With an increasing demand for snails, improved snail farming techniques are needed to increase production while protecting the environment and animal biodiversity. This project will assist 750 local families&#x2014;at least 50 percent of whom are women or girls&#x2014;for five years, improving nutrition by alleviating protein deficiency, increasing household income and contributing to biodiversity conservation and sustainable management of forest resources. Originally, 250 families will receive 1,000 snails each and then pass on the gift to another 250 families in the second year, who will in turn pass on to another 250 families in the project&#x2019;s fourth year.</narrative>
  </description>
